# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mass-spectrometry-chem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Mass spectrometry using ESI is called electrospray ionization mass spectrometry (ESI-MS) or, less commonly, electrospray mass spectrometry (ES-MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] ESI is a so-called 'soft ionization' technique, since there is very little fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] This can be advantageous in the sense that the molecular ion (or more accurately a pseudo molecular ion) is almost always observed, however very little structural information can be gained from the simple mass spectrum obtained.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] This disadvantage can be overcome by coupling ESI with tandem mass spectrometry (ESI-MS/MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Another important advantage of ESI is that solution-phase information can be retained into the gas-phase.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray ionization technique was first reported by Masamichi Yamashita and John Fenn in 1984, and independently by Lidia Gall and co-workers in Soviet Union, also in 1984.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Gall's work was not recognised or translated in the western scientific literature until a translation was published in 2008.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The development of electrospray ionization for the analysis of biological macromolecules was rewarded with the attribution of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry to John Bennett Fenn and Koichi Tanaka in 2002.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] One of the original instruments used by Fenn is on display at the Science History Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] In 1882, Lord Rayleigh theoretically estimated the maximum amount of charge a liquid droplet could carry before throwing out fine jets of liquid.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] This is now known as the Rayleigh limit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] In 1914, John Zeleny published work on the behaviour of fluid droplets at the end of glass capillaries and presented evidence for different electrospray modes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Wilson and Taylor and Nolan investigated electrospray in the 1920s and Macky in 1931.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray cone (now known as the Taylor cone) was described by Sir Geoffrey Ingram Taylor.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The first use of electrospray ionization with mass spectrometry was reported by Malcolm Dole in 1968.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] John Bennett Fenn was awarded the 2002 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the development of electrospray ionization mass spectrometry in the late 1980s.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The liquid containing the analytes of interest (typically 10−6 - 10−4 M needed ) is dispersed by electrospray, into a fine aerosol.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Because the ion formation involves extensive solvent evaporation (also termed desolvation), the typical solvents for electrospray ionization are prepared by mixing water with volatile organic compounds (e.g. methanol acetonitrile).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] To decrease the initial droplet size, compounds that increase the conductivity (e.g. acetic acid) are customarily added to the solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] These species also act to provide a source of protons to facilitate the ionization process.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Large-flow electrosprays can benefit from nebulization of a heated inert gas such as nitrogen or carbon dioxide in addition to the high temperature of the ESI source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The aerosol is sampled into the first vacuum stage of a mass spectrometer through a capillary carrying a potential difference of approximately 3000 V, which can be heated to aid further solvent evaporation from the charged droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The solvent evaporates from a charged droplet until it becomes unstable upon reaching its Rayleigh limit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] At this point, the droplet deforms as the electrostatic repulsion of like charges, in an ever-decreasing droplet size, becomes more powerful than the surface tension holding the droplet together.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] At this point the droplet undergoes Coulomb fission, whereby the original droplet 'explodes' creating many smaller, more stable droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The new droplets undergo desolvation and subsequently further Coulomb fissions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] During the fission, the droplet loses a small percentage of its mass (1.0–2.3%) along with a relatively large percentage of its charge (10–18%).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] There are two major theories that explain the final production of gas-phase ions: the ion evaporation model (IEM) and the charge residue model (CRM).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The IEM suggests that as the droplet reaches a certain radius the field strength at the surface of the droplet becomes large enough to assist the field desorption of solvated ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The CRM suggests that electrospray droplets undergo evaporation and fission cycles, eventually leading progeny droplets that contain on average one analyte ion or less.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The gas-phase ions form after the remaining solvent molecules evaporate, leaving the analyte with the charges that the droplet carried.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] A large body of evidence shows either directly or indirectly that small ions (from small molecules) are liberated into the gas phase through the ion evaporation mechanism, while larger ions (from folded proteins for instance) form by charged residue mechanism.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] A third model invoking combined charged residue-field emission has been proposed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Another model called chain ejection model (CEM) is proposed for disordered polymers (unfolded proteins).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The ions observed by mass spectrometry may be quasimolecular ions created by the addition of a hydrogen cation and denoted [**M** + H]+, or of another cation such as sodium ion, [**M** + Na]+, or the removal of a hydrogen nucleus, [**M** − H]−.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Multiply charged ions such as [**M** + *n*H]*n*+ are often observed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] For large macromolecules, there can be many charge states, resulting in a characteristic charge state envelope.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] All these are even-electron ion species: electrons (alone) are not added or removed, unlike in some other ionization sources.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The analytes are sometimes involved in electrochemical processes, leading to shifts of the corresponding peaks in the mass spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] This effect is demonstrated in the direct ionization of noble metals such as copper, silver and gold using electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The efficiency of generating the gas phase ions for small molecules in ESI varies depending on the compound structure, the solvent used and instrumental parameters.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The differences in ionization efficiency reach more than 1 million times.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The electrosprays operated at low flow rates generate much smaller initial droplets, which ensure improved ionization efficiency.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Smith reported significant sensitivity increases could be achieved using lower flow rates, and down to 200 nL/min.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] In 1994, two research groups coined the name micro-electrospray (microspray) for electrosprays working at low flow rates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Emmett and Caprioli demonstrated improved performance for HPLC-MS analyses when the electrospray was operated at 300–800 nL/min.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Wilm and Mann demonstrated that a capillary flow of ~ 25 nL/min can sustain an electrospray at the tip of emitters fabricated by pulling glass capillaries to a few micrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The latter was renamed nano-electrospray (nanospray) in 1996.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Currently the name nanospray is also in use for electrosprays fed by pumps at low flow rates, not only for self-fed electrosprays.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Although there may not be a well-defined flow rate range for electrospray, microspray, and nano-electrospray, studied "changes in analyte partition during droplet fission prior to ion release".
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] In this paper, they compare results obtained by three other groups. and then measure the signal intensity ratio [Ba2+ + Ba+]/[BaBr+] at different flow rates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Cold spray ionization is a form of electrospray in which the solution containing the sample is forced through a small cold capillary (10–80 °C) into an electric field to create a fine mist of cold charged droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Applications of this method include the analysis of fragile molecules and guest-host interactions that cannot be studied using regular electrospray ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization has also been achieved at pressures as low as 25 torr and termed subambient pressure ionization with nanoelectrospray (SPIN) based upon a two-stage ion funnel interface developed by Richard D.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The SPIN implementation provided increased sensitivity due to the use of ion funnels that helped confine and transfer ions to the lower pressure region of the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Nanoelectrospray emitter is made out of a fine capillary with a small aperture about 1–3 micrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] For sufficient conductivity this capillary is usually sputter-coated with conductive material, e.g. gold.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Nanoelectrospray ionization consumes only a few microliters of a sample and forms smaller droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Operation at low pressure was particularly effective for low flow rates where the smaller electrospray droplet size allowed effective desolvation and ion formation to be achieved.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] As a result, the researchers were later able to demonstrate achieving an excess of 50% overall ionization utilization efficiency for transfer of ions from the liquid phase, into the gas phase as ions, and through the dual ion funnel interface to the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] In ambient ionization, the formation of ions occurs outside the mass spectrometer without sample preparation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray is used for ion formation in a number of ambient ion sources.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Desorption electrospray ionization (DESI) is an ambient ionization technique in which a solvent electrospray is directed at a sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray is attracted to the surface by applying a voltage to the sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Sample compounds are extracted into the solvent which is again aerosolized as highly charged droplets that evaporate to form highly charged ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] After ionization, the ions enter the atmospheric pressure interface of the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] DESI allows for ambient ionization of samples at atmospheric pressure, with little sample preparation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Extractive electrospray ionization is a spray-type, ambient ionization method that uses two merged sprays, one of which is generated by electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Laser-based electrospray-based ambient ionization is a two-step process in which a pulsed laser is used to desorb or ablate material from a sample and the plume of material interacts with an electrospray to create ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] For ambient ionization, the sample material is deposited on a target near the electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The laser desorbs or ablates material from the sample which is ejected from the surface and into the electrospray which produces highly charged ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Examples are electrospray laser desorption ionization, matrix-assisted laser desorption electrospray ionization, and laser ablation electrospray ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Electrostatic spray ionization (ESTASI) involved the analysis of samples located on a flat or porous surface, or inside a microchannel.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] A droplet containing analytes is deposited on a sample area, to which a pulsed high voltage to is applied.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] When the electrostatic pressure is larger than the surface tension, droplets and ions are sprayed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Secondary electrospray ionization (SESI) is an spray type, ambient ionization method where charging ions are produced by means of an electrospray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] These ions then charge vapor molecules in the gas phase when colliding with them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] In paper spray ionization, the sample is applied to a piece of paper, solvent is added, and a high voltage is applied to the paper, creating ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray is used to study protein folding.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization is the ion source of choice to couple liquid chromatography with mass spectrometry (LC-MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The analysis can be performed online, by feeding the liquid eluting from the LC column directly to an electrospray, or offline, by collecting fractions to be later analyzed in a classical nanoelectrospray-mass spectrometry setup.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Among the numerous operating parameters in ESI-MS, for proteins, the electrospray voltage has been identified as an important parameter to consider in ESI LC/MS gradient elution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The effect of various solvent compositions (such as TFA or ammonium acetate, or supercharging reagents, or derivitizing groups) or spraying conditions on electrospray-LCMS spectra and/or nanoESI-MS spectra. have been studied.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Capillary electrophoresis-mass spectrometry was enabled by an ESI interface that was developed and patented by Richard D.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Smith and coworkers at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, and shown to have broad utility for the analysis of very small biological and chemical compound mixtures, and even extending to a single biological cell.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization is also utilized in studying noncovalent gas phase interactions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] The electrospray process is thought to be capable of transferring liquid-phase noncovalent complexes into the gas phase without disrupting the noncovalent interaction.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Problems such as non specific interactions have been identified when studying ligand substrate complexes by ESI-MS or nanoESI-MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] An interesting example of this is studying the interactions between enzymes and drugs which are inhibitors of the enzyme.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Competition studies between STAT6 and inhibitors have used ESI as a way to screen for potential new drug candidates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/electrospray-ionization] Electrospray ionization can even be used for studying protein complexes >1 MDa.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a typical MS procedure, a sample, which may be solid, liquid, or gaseous, is ionized, for example by bombarding it with a beam of electrons.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This may cause some of the sample's molecules to break up into positively charged fragments or simply become positively charged without fragmenting.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] These ions (fragments) are then separated according to their mass-to-charge ratio, for example by accelerating them and subjecting them to an electric or magnetic field: ions of the same mass-to-charge ratio will undergo the same amount of deflection.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ions are detected by a mechanism capable of detecting charged particles, such as an electron multiplier.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Results are displayed as spectra of the signal intensity of detected ions as a function of the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The atoms or molecules in the sample can be identified by correlating known masses (e.g. an entire molecule) to the identified masses or through a characteristic fragmentation pattern.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 1886, Eugen Goldstein observed rays in gas discharges under low pressure that traveled away from the anode and through channels in a perforated cathode, opposite to the direction of negatively charged cathode rays (which travel from cathode to anode).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Goldstein called these positively charged anode rays "Kanalstrahlen"; the standard translation of this term into English is "canal rays".
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Wilhelm Wien found that strong electric or magnetic fields deflected the canal rays and, in 1899, constructed a device with perpendicular electric and magnetic fields that separated the positive rays according to their charge-to-mass ratio (*Q/m*).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Wien found that the charge-to-mass ratio depended on the nature of the gas in the discharge tube.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thomson later improved on the work of Wien by reducing the pressure to create the mass spectrograph.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The word *spectrograph* had become part of the international scientific vocabulary by 1884.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Early *spectrometry* devices that measured the mass-to-charge ratio of ions were called *mass spectrographs* which consisted of instruments that recorded a spectrum of mass values on a photographic plate.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A *mass spectroscope* is similar to a *mass spectrograph* except that the beam of ions is directed onto a phosphor screen.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A mass spectroscope configuration was used in early instruments when it was desired that the effects of adjustments be quickly observed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Once the instrument was properly adjusted, a photographic plate was inserted and exposed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The term mass spectroscope continued to be used even though the direct illumination of a phosphor screen was replaced by indirect measurements with an oscilloscope.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The use of the term *mass spectroscopy* is now discouraged due to the possibility of confusion with light spectroscopy.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass spectrometry is often abbreviated as *mass-spec* or simply as *MS*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Modern techniques of mass spectrometry were devised by Arthur Jeffrey Dempster and F.W.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sector mass spectrometers known as calutrons were developed by Ernest O.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Lawrence and used for separating the isotopes of uranium during the Manhattan Project.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Calutron mass spectrometers were used for uranium enrichment at the Oak Ridge, Tennessee Y-12 plant established during World War II.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 1989, half of the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Hans Dehmelt and Wolfgang Paul for the development of the ion trap technique in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In 2002, the Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to John Bennett Fenn for the development of electrospray ionization (ESI) and Koichi Tanaka for the development of soft laser desorption and their application to the ionization of biological macromolecules, especially proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A mass spectrometer consists of 5 components: **sample inlet**, **ion source** (or **ionizer**), **mass analyzer**, **detector**, data system.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Each component can be varied somewhat independently from the other components, and the full mass spectrometer itself can be included as a component in an analysis pipeline, allowing great flexibility.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample inlet prepares the sample to be analyzed in a suitable state.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion source takes samples from the sample inlet, converts a portion of the sample into a stream of ions, and outputs it to the mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] There is a wide variety of ionization techniques, depending on the phase (solid, liquid, gas) of the sample and the efficiency of various ionization mechanisms for the unknown species.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] An extraction system removes ions from the sample, which are then targeted into the mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The mass analyzer takes an input stream of ions and separates ("analyzes") its constituent ions according to their *m/z*, the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The detector measures the value of an indicator quantity and thus provides data for calculating the abundances of each ion present.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some detectors also give spatial information, e.g., a multichannel plate.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The following describes the operation of a simple mass spectrometer that uses sector type.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consider a sample of sodium chloride (table salt).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In the ion source, the sample is vaporized (turned into gas) and ionized (transformed into electrically charged particles) into sodium (Na+) and chloride (Cl−) ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sodium atoms and ions are monoisotopic, with a mass of about 23 daltons (symbol: Da or older symbol: u).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Chloride atoms and ions come in two stable isotopes with masses of approximately 35 u (at a natural abundance of about 75 percent) and approximately 37 u (at a natural abundance of about 25 percent).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The analyzer part of the spectrometer contains electric and magnetic fields, which exert forces on ions traveling through these fields.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The speed of a charged particle may be increased or decreased while passing through the electric field, and its direction may be altered by the magnetic field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The magnitude of the deflection of the moving ion's trajectory depends on its mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Lighter ions are deflected by the magnetic force to a greater degree than heavier ions (based on Newton's second law of motion, *F* = *ma*).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The streams of magnetically sorted ions pass from the analyzer to the detector, which records the relative abundance of each ion type.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This information is used to determine the chemical element composition of the original sample (i.e. that both sodium and chlorine are present in the sample) and the isotopic composition of its constituents (the ratio of 35Cl to 37Cl).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample inlet provides a stream of neutral molecules, so that the ion source can ionize them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The classical design produces the stream of molecules in the form of a low-pressure gas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is low-pressure, so that molecules within the stream does not frequently collide with each other.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions must travel without frequent collisions, because the instrument separates ions by their motion in electric and magnetic fields.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Despite being low-pressure, the sample stream is still at a much higher pressure than the rest of the system, which is held in a greater vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, the sample stream can only enter the ion source chamber via a small pinhole, called a **molecular leak**.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample itself is already a gas, then the sample inlet can simply be a gas inlet with pressure valve.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is a volatile liquid or solid, then it can simply be placed in a chamber, vacuum-pumped to a low pressure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is not sufficiently volatile, the sample inlet can be fitted within an oven.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the sample is too nonvolatile to be turned into a low-pressure gas, then one can use a **direct probe**.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The direct probe is a probe with a tip of thin wire loop, pin, or a capillary tube.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The probe is inserted through a vacuum lock into the ionization chamber, so that the tip is close to the ion source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The probe can be heated to increase vapor pressure further.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Such a system is effective for samples with vapor pressures lower than $10^{-9}$ mmHg at room temperature.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample can be prepared by an earlier analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, it can simply be the gaseous output of a gas chromatography machine as in GC-MS, or the liquid output of a high-performance liquid chromatography machine, as in HPLC-MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The recently developed "atmospheric pressure ionization" techniques allow us to entirely dispense with the sample inlet.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion source is the part of the mass spectrometer that transforms the sample from the sample inlet into a stream of ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many techniques with various dimensions for tradeoffs between different choices of ion sources, in terms of monetary cost, accuracy, precision, compatibility with other stages of spectroscopy, ease of use, etc.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, EI is not suitable for coupling to HPLC, i.e.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] LC-MS, since at atmospheric pressure, the filaments used to generate electrons burn out rapidly.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thus EI is coupled predominantly with GC, i.e.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] GC-MS, where the entire system is under high vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Two techniques often used with liquid and solid biological samples include electrospray ionization (invented by John Fenn) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI, initially developed as a similar technique Soft Laser Desorption) by K.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tanaka for which a Nobel Prize was awarded and as MALDI by M.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Hard ionization techniques are those that impart high quantities of residual internal energy in the subject molecule, even after ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Part of the energy would be dissipated by rupturing chemical bonds within the ion, producing many fragmentary radical ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The resultant ions tend to have *m/z* lower than the molecular ion (other than in the case of proton transfer and not including isotope peaks).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The most common example of hard ionization is electron ionization (EI).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The radical ions produced after the first ionization are called second-generation product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The products are then directed towards the mass analyzer by a repeller electrode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ionization process often follows predictable cleavage reactions that give rise to fragment ions which, following detection and signal processing, convey structural information about the analyte.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Conversely, soft ionization techniques are those that impart little residual energy onto the subject molecule and as such result in little fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Examples include fast atom bombardment (FAB), chemical ionization (CI), atmospheric-pressure chemical ionization (APCI), atmospheric-pressure photoionization (APPI), electrospray ionization (ESI), desorption electrospray ionization (DESI), and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In electron ionization (EI), energetic electrons are produced by a hot cathode: a wire filament heated by running electric current through it, producing energetic electrons by thermionic emission.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The electrons are then accelerated towards an anode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The voltage difference between the cathode and the anode determines the energy of the electron stream.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Most organic compounds have ionization energy 8-15 eV, but empirically, the efficiency of ionization is too low unless the electron beam has an energy of 50-70 eV per electron.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The spectral features, including fragmentation patterns, depend on the energy setting.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Conventionally for EI, the electron energy is standardized to be exactly 70 eV.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, if one wishes to compare their EI-MS results against standard databases, or produce results that can be added to standard databases, one must standardize their EI electron energy to 70 eV.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI accepts as input a stream of gas from the molecular leak.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The gas stream crosses the electron stream perpendicularly.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion stream then is accerelated by a succession of electrodes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically an ion carrying 1 e would be accelerated to 1-10 keV.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI has many benefits for routine mass spectrometry of small organic molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is cheap and robust, with reproducible spectrograms.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Databases for EI spectrograms are widely available and covers many such molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] EI is unsuited for large molecules, such as most biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is a hard technique, which tends to break down large molecule ions during flight, since large molecules are particularly easy to fragment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Furthermore, large molecules are hard to volatilize without being degraded by heat.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In chemical ionization (CI), the analyte is ionized by a chemical reaction with an ionized reagent gas (itself ionized by some technique, such as by EI).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The analyte gas and the reagent gas intersect, and react.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The reaction then produces ionized analyte fragments by various mechanisms, including proton transfer, electron transfer, and adduct formation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ion is then accelerated electrostatically, as in EI.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] CI ion sources are similar to EI sources, and most modern mass spectrometers can switch from EI to CI mode in minutes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] To ensure efficiency, the amount of reagent is much higher than the analyte.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, a large amount of reagent ions would end up in the mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is usually handled by only measuring the part of the spectrogram with *m/z* above those of the main species in the reagent ion stream.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Common ionizing reagents for CI-MS include methane, ammonia, isobutane, and methanol.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The proton affinity of the reagent gas and of the sample should be matched to ensure efficient ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the proton affinity of the reagent gas is too high, ionization is inefficient.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the proton affinity of the reagent gas is too low, fragmentation is excessive.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Electrospray ionization (ESI) and thermospray ionization (TSI) are suited for high molecular weight biomolecules and other labile or nonvolatile compounds, and especially in a LC-MS system.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In both cases, the analyte is in a solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The solution is sprayed out, by either electrospraying or thermospraying, into a stream of mist, which then evaporates into an ion stream.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] TSI has been supplanted by ESI for most purposes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In TSI, the solution enters a heated capillary, producing a spray of droplets.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The solvent evaporates, leaving ionized analytes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In ESI, the solution enters a capillary held at a high voltage (usually 2-5 kV), producing an electrospray into a heated chamber against a counterflow of a drying gas (usually nitrogen).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The charge density increases on a droplet as it evaporates, until the electrostatic energy overcomes the surface tension energy, exploding the droplet.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This process repeats, ending with an ion stream without the solvent.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Unlike in TSI, the analyte ions produced by ESI may carry a different amount of charge than the same analyte would carry in the solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] That is, an analyte that is naturally occurring as M+ in the solution may end up becoming a stream of ions containing a mixture of M+, M2+, M3+, etc.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typical proteins can carry many protons due to the presence of basic amino acid side chains, resulting in peaks at *m/z* = 600–2000 for proteins with a molecular weight ~200,000 Da.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is convenient, since it means the ion would not exceed the *m/z* limits on typical mass analyzers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Desorption ionization (DI) is a family of ionization techniques.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The main examples are secondary-ion mass spectrometry (SIMS), fast atom bombardment (FAB), and matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In DI, the sample is dissolved or dispersed in a matrix, and bombarded by a high-energy (1-10 keV) beam of ions (SIMS), neutral atoms (FAB), or photons (MALDI).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The beam ionizes and expels (desorbs) some sample molecules off the matrix.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The matrix should be nonvolatile and relatively inert, so that it would not react with the analyte.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It should also be a good electrolyte to allow ion formation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ionized fragments of the matrix itself forms usually have $m/z\lesssim 600$ , so the spectrogram usually filters out that segment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] SIMS uses an ion beam, usually Ar+ or Cs+.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] FAB uses a neutral atom beam, usually Ar or Xe.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] For SIMS and FAB, if the matrix compound is more acidic than the analyte, then predominantly (M + H)+ forms formed, and conversely (M − H)−.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Also possibly forming (M + Na)+, (M + K)+, etc, if the matrix is contaminated incidentally (adventitiously) by sodium, potassium, etc.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typical matrix materials include glycerol, thioglycerol, 3-nitrobenzyl alcohol, diethanolamine, triethanolamine, and dithiothreitol-dithioerythritol mixture.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are usually used to analyze polypeptides and oligonucleotides up to 20 kDa.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDE uses a photon beam, usually the soft-UV 337 nm nitrogen laser.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It can also use an infrared (IR) laser for direct analysis of samples contained in gels or thin-layer chromatography (TLC) plates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDE can analyze small polymers (~1 kDa), to oligosaccharides, oligonucleotides and polypeptides, antibodies, up to small proteins (~300 kDa).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is highly sensitive, requiring only femtomoles of sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Desorption/ionization on silicon (DIOS) is similar to MALDE, but without the matrix.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample is deposited directly on a nanostructured (porous silicon) surface and the sample desorbed directly from the nanostructured surface through the adsorption of laser light energy.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] DIOS has been used to analyze organic molecules, metabolites, biomolecules and peptides, and, ultimately, to image tissues and cells.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Inductively coupled plasma (ICP) sources are used primarily for cation analysis of a wide array of sample types.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In this source, a plasma that is electrically neutral overall, but that has had a substantial fraction of its atoms ionized by high temperature, is used to atomize introduced sample molecules and to further strip the outer electrons from those atoms.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The plasma is usually generated from argon gas, since the first ionization energy of argon atoms is higher than the first of any other elements except He, F and Ne, but lower than the second ionization energy of all except the most electropositive metals.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The heating is achieved by a radio-frequency current passed through a coil surrounding the plasma.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Photoionization can be used in experiments which seek to use mass spectrometry as a means of resolving chemical kinetics mechanisms and isomeric product branching.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In such instances a high energy photon, either X-ray or uv, is used to dissociate stable gaseous molecules in a carrier gas of He or Ar.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In instances where a synchrotron light source is utilized, a tuneable photon energy can be utilized to acquire a photoionization efficiency curve which can be used in conjunction with the charge ratio *m/z* to fingerprint molecular and ionic species.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] More recently atmospheric pressure photoionization (APPI) has been developed to ionize molecules mostly as effluents of LC-MS systems.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some applications for ambient ionization include environmental applications as well as clinical applications.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In these techniques, ions form in an ion source outside the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Sampling becomes easy as the samples don't need previous separation nor preparation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Others include glow discharge, field desorption (FD), spark ionization and thermal ionization (TIMS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass analyzers separate the ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many types of mass analyzers, using either static or dynamic fields, magnetic or electric fields.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Each analyzer type has its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Many mass spectrometers use two or more mass analyzers for tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In addition to the more common mass analyzers listed below, there are others designed for special situations.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] of motion in the non-relativistic case, i.e. valid only at ion velocity much lower than the speed of light).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This differential equation is the classic equation of motion for charged particles.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Together with the particle's initial conditions, it completely determines the particle's motion in space and time in terms of *m/Q*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thus mass spectrometers could be thought of as "mass-to-charge spectrometers".
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] When presenting data, it is common to use the (officially) dimensionless *m/z*, where z is the number of elementary charges (*e*) on the ion (z=Q/e).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This quantity, although it is informally called the mass-to-charge ratio, more accurately speaking represents the ratio of the mass number and the charge number, *z*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are several important analyzer characteristics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **mass resolving power** $\Delta (m/z)$ is the just detectable difference in *m/z*, at that particular *m/z*, usually measured measured in milli mass units (mDa).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In particular, the resolution may be different at different *m/z*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is usually operationalized as the full width at half maximum a peak at that given *m/z*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A "high-resolution" mass analyzer typically has resolution >1 million.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Concretely, that means it can resolve two peaks at ~1 kDa, differing by just ~1 mDa.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **absolute accuracy** is the ratio of the *m/z* measurement error to the true *m/z*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **mass range** is the range of *m/z* that a given analyzer can analyze.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **speed** is the number of spectra lines per unit time that can be generated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically, higher resolution requires lower speed, and vice versa.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some mass spectrometers, such as the Fourier transform spectrometers, allow a continuous tradeoff between speed and resolution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A sector-type mass analyzer uses a static electric and/or magnetic field to control the path of the ion beam.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The most common type uses a magnetic field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a simplified case, the field is a constant field B , and we have an ion of mass m and charge $ze$ that enters the field perpendicularly at velocity v .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Then, in the field, the ion undergoes circular motion of radius $R={\tfrac {v(m/z)}{Be}}$ .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ionizer has accelerated the ion under a known voltage V , then the kinetic energy of the ion is $KE=zeV={\tfrac {1}{2}}mv^{2}$ , giving $m/z={\frac {eR^{2}B^{2}}{2V}}$ Thus, the single input ion beam is analyzed into a fan of ion beams, the higher m/z ions turning at a larger radius.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] One can then select for one m/z by using a moving narrow slit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] One can also use a fixed narrow slit, but vary V or B .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If there is just a single detector, then the analyzer can sweep across the mass spectrum one slit at a time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] With multiple detectors, the speed of analysis increases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A pure magnetic sector analyzer can achieve resolution ~10,000.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] With an added electrostatic focusing field before or after the magnetic sector, the analyzer can achieve resolution ~100,000.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Particularly unstable ions may disintegrate while passing through the analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If it undergoes the reaction Mz+ → M'z+ + (other parts) when entering the analyzer, it would undergo a circular motion of radius $R'={\tfrac {v(m'/z)}{Be}}$ .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This would then show up in the resulting spectrogram as a peak that is *apparently* made by an ion with $(m^{*}/z)=({\tfrac {m'^{2}}{m}}/z)$ .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Since there is no actual ion with mass $m^{*}$ , this is called an abnormal peak, or a **metastable ion peak**.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In general, a meta stable ion peak is a broad peak centered at a highly non-integer value of $m^{*}/z$ .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The existence of a metastable ion peak at $({\tfrac {m'^{2}}{m}}/z)$ is strong evidence that two ions of masses $m/z,m'/z$ are in fact related by the reaction Mz+ → M'z+ + (other parts).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The time-of-flight (TOF) analyzer takes as input a short *pulse* of ions, and lets it fly through a long vacuum tube.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions with different m/z would arrive at the end of the tube at different times, thus analyzing them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The ions must enter the tube as pulses, because otherwise the TOF cannot be measured.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ionizer outputs a continuous stream of ions, then it must be cut up into ion pulses, by methods such as a fast mechanical shutter, an oscillating electric field plus a narrow slit, etc.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The MALDI ionizer is particularly well-suited for TOF analyzer, since the laser used in MALDI is usually a high-intensity pulse laser.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] MALDI-TOF has allowed measurement of mass spetrograms using only a few attomoles of material.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Concretely, let the length of the analyzer be L , then the time taken for an ion of velocity v to pass through the analyzer is $t=L/v$ .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In that case, we have $m/z=(m/z)_{0}+{\frac {4eVt_{0}}{L^{2}}}\delta t$ This means that the signal can be measured by an oscilloscope in trigger mode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Indeed, the first GC-MS was done in 1950 using an oscilloscope.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The experimenters took quick photos of the oscilloscope screen for each component exiting the gas chromatography machine.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This distribution in velocities broadens the peaks shown on the count vs *m/z* plot, but will generally not change the central location of the peaks, since the starting velocity of ions is generally centered at zero.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] To fix this problem, time-lag focusing/delayed extraction has been coupled with TOF-MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ions do not start at identical kinetic energies, then some ions may lag behind higher kinetic energy ions decreasing resolution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Reflectron geometries are commonly employed to correct this problem.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Longer tubes result in higher resolution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A reflector doubles the effective tube length.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A reflector-TOF can reach a resolution of several thousands.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] For their low resolution, TOF mass spectrometers makes up for it in speed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are particularly useful in chemical kinetics studies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It can study rapid reactions such as combustion and explosions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A quadrupole mass analyzers uses four parallel metal rods to create a quadrupole electrical field oscillating at radio frequency (RF), to selectively stabilize or destabilize the paths of ions passing through.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] With each oscillation pattern, the ions passing through would undergo a helical motion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] If the ion has *m/z* within a certain range, the helical motion is stable.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Otherwise, the helical motion will increase in amplitude until the ion collides with the rods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This means that only ions with m/z within a narrow range can go through it.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The full spectrogram can be swept through by changing the potentials on the rods, continuously or in a succession of discrete hops.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are typically of low resolution ~1000, but they are cheap and small, so are good for "desktop" mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole mass filter is closely related to the quadrupole ion trap, particularly the linear quadrupole ion trap except that it is designed to pass the untrapped ions rather than collect the trapped ones, and is for that reason referred to as a **transmission quadrupole**.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole ion trap itself can be used as an analyzer, as in ion trap analyzers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A common variation of the transmission quadrupole is the triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The "triple quad" has three consecutive quadrupole stages, the first acting as a mass filter to transmit a particular incoming ion to the second quadrupole, a collision chamber, wherein that ion can be broken into fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The third quadrupole also acts as a mass filter, to transmit a particular fragment ion to the detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is a kind of MS/MS, and so it can perform various scan types characteristic of MS/MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A magnetically enhanced quadrupole mass analyzer has an additional magnetic field, axial or transverse.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The quadrupole ion trap works on the same physical principles as the quadrupole mass analyzer, but the ions are trapped and sequentially ejected.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions are trapped in a mainly quadrupole RF field, in a space defined by a ring electrode (usually connected to the main RF potential) between two endcap electrodes (typically connected to DC or auxiliary AC potentials).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The sample is ionized either internally (e.g. with an electron or laser beam), or externally, in which case the ions are often introduced through an aperture in an endcap electrode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many mass/charge separation and isolation methods but the most commonly used is the mass instability mode in which the RF potential is ramped so that the orbit of ions with a mass *a* > *b* are stable while ions with mass *b* become unstable and are ejected on the *z*-axis onto a detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are also non-destructive analysis methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The cylindrical ion trap mass spectrometer (CIT) is a derivative of the quadrupole ion trap where the electrodes are formed from flat rings rather than hyperbolic shaped electrodes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The architecture lends itself well to miniaturization because as the size of a trap is reduced, the shape of the electric field near the center of the trap, the region where the ions are trapped, forms a shape similar to that of a hyperbolic trap.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A linear quadrupole ion trap is similar to a quadrupole ion trap, but it traps ions in a two dimensional quadrupole field, instead of a three-dimensional quadrupole field as in a 3D quadrupole ion trap.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Thermo Fisher's LTQ ("linear trap quadrupole") is an example of the linear ion trap.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A toroidal ion trap can be visualized as a linear quadrupole curved around and connected at the ends or as a cross-section of a 3D ion trap rotated on edge to form the toroid, donut-shaped trap.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The trap can store large volumes of ions by distributing them throughout the ring-like trap structure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This toroidal shaped trap is a configuration that allows the increased miniaturization of an ion trap mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Additionally, all ions are stored in the same trapping field and ejected together simplifying detection that can be complicated with array configurations due to variations in detector alignment and machining of the arrays.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] As with the toroidal trap, linear traps and 3D quadrupole ion traps are the most commonly miniaturized mass analyzers due to their high sensitivity, tolerance for mTorr pressure, and capabilities for single analyzer tandem mass spectrometry (e.g. product ion scans).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Fourier-transform mass spectrometry (FTMS), or more precisely Fourier-transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry (FT-ICR MS), measures mass by detecting the image current produced by ions spiralling in the presence of a magnetic field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Instead of measuring the deflection of ions with a detector such as an electron multiplier, the ions are injected into a Penning trap (a static electric/magnetic ion trap) where they effectively form part of a circuit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Detectors at fixed positions in space measure the electrical signal of ions which pass near them over time, producing a periodic signal.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Since the frequency of an ion's cycling is determined by its *m/z* ratio, this can be deconvoluted by Fourier transform on the signal.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ion cyclotron resonance (ICR) is an older mass analysis technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It is similar to FTMS, in that the ions undergo cyclotron resonane.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, the ions are detected with a traditional detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions trapped in a Penning trap are excited by an RF electric field until they impact the wall of the trap, where the detector is located.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions of different mass are resolved according to impact time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] FTMS is generally the most sensitive analyzer on the market, achieving resolution ~1 million.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It achieves such high resolution, since each ion is "counted" multiple times by the spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] From the perspective of the uncertainty principle of signal processing, an oscillating signal that is highly *delocalized* in time is also highly *localized* in frequency.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Orbitrap analyzers are similar to FTMS analyzers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Ions are electrostatically trapped in an orbit around a central, spindle shaped electrode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The electrode confines the ions so that they both orbit around the central electrode and oscillate back and forth along the central electrode's long axis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This oscillation generates an image current in the detector plates which is recorded by the instrument.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The frequencies of these image currents depend on the mass-to-charge ratios of the ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Mass spectra are obtained by Fourier transformation of the recorded image currents.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Orbitraps have a high mass accuracy, high sensitivity and a good dynamic range.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Some chemical species have the same chemical composition, but different isotopes (isotopomers).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] They can be distinguished by a very basic analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Indeed, isotopes were discovered in 1922, very early in the history of mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] However, two chemical species can have the same number of nucleons (neutrons and protons).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, C3 and SH4 both have 36 nucleons.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] They can still be distinguished, since proton and neutron mass differ by 1.4 mDa, and since different nuclei have different binding energy, which by $E=mc^{2}$ results in a different mass.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The net result is that C3 and S1H4 differ by 3.4 mDa.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Even smaller differences are achievable by carefully matching isotopes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, C4 and S1H313C1 differ by 1.1 mDa.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Such differences can be resolved by high resolution mass spectrometry, which reaches resolution >1 million, sufficient to resolve ~1 mDa difference at *m/z* ~ 1000.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] There are many techniques for high resolution MS, but the highest resolution is achieved by FTMS with high magnetic field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] With increasing magnetic field strength, the resolution and spectral acquisition speed increases linearly, while mass accuracy and dynamic range increases quadratically.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Consequently, the highest resolution is achieved by high field FTMS, up to 21 Tesla.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It reaches resolution >2.7 million at m/z ~ 400, and mass measurement accuracy < 80 ppb.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] They are often employed in geochemical and petrochemical studies, since there is a lot of money in petroleum industry, and petroleum composition is highly complex.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Another application is in isotopic analysis of large proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Two proteins differing by a single isotopic atom are separated by $\Delta m\approx 1$ , requiring a resolution of $m/\Delta m$ to resolve.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] For large proteins with m > 100 kDa and z ~ 50, such as monoclonal antibodies, this requires an analyzer that achieves resolving power > 100,000 at m/z ~ 2000.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] High resolution FTMS is also very sensitive as a detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] It has allowed detecting proteins in the 8–20 kDa range at a sample concentration of ~30 zeptomole (i.e. about 20,000 *individual* molecules).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] When the mass of a single ion species is to be measured, the highest precision achievable is via Penning-type traps.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The PENTATRAP for example measures the mass of long-lived, highly charged, heavy ions, to a precision of $m/\Delta m>10^{11}$ .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] This is sufficiently sensitive to directly measure the energy of metastable electronic states to an accuracy of ~1 eV via the mass-energy equation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The final element of the mass spectrometer is the detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The detector records either the charge induced or the current produced when an ion passes by or hits a surface.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In a scanning instrument, the signal produced in the detector during the course of the scan versus where the instrument is in the scan (at what *m/Q*) will produce a mass spectrum, a record of ions as a function of *m/Q*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **linear dynamic range** is the range over which the detector signal is linear with analyte concentration.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Typically, some type of electron multiplier is used, though other detectors including Faraday cups and ion-to-photon detectors are also used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Because the number of ions leaving the mass analyzer at a particular instant is typically quite small, considerable amplification is often necessary to get a signal.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Microchannel plate detectors are commonly used in modern commercial instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In FTMS and Orbitraps, the detector consists of a pair of metal surfaces within the mass analyzer/ion trap region which the ions only pass near as they oscillate.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] No direct current is produced, only a weak AC image current is produced in a circuit between the electrodes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Other inductive detectors have also been used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A tandem mass spectrometer is one capable of multiple rounds of mass spectrometry, usually separated by some form of molecule fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] For example, one mass analyzer can isolate one peptide from many entering a mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A collision cell then stabilizes the peptide ions while they collide with a gas, causing them to fragment by collision-induced dissociation (CID).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] A further mass analyzer then sorts the fragments produced from the peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tandem MS can also be done in a single mass analyzer over time, as in a quadrupole ion trap.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] An important application using tandem mass spectrometry is in protein identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Tandem mass spectrometry enables a variety of experimental sequences.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Many commercial mass spectrometers are designed to expedite the execution of such routine sequences as selected reaction monitoring, precursor ion scanning, product ion scanning, and neutral loss scanning.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Another type of tandem mass spectrometry used for radiocarbon dating is accelerator mass spectrometry, which uses very high voltages, usually in the mega-volt range, to accelerate negative ions into a type of tandem mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The **METLIN Metabolite and Chemical Entity Database** is the largest repository of experimental tandem mass spectrometry data acquired from standards.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] The tandem mass spectrometry data on over 960,000 molecular standards (as of October 2025) is provided to facilitate the identification of chemical entities from tandem mass spectrometry experiments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] In addition to the identification of known molecules it is also useful for identifying unknowns using its similarity searching/analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] All tandem mass spectrometry data comes from the experimental analysis of standards at multiple collision energies and in both positive and negative ionization modes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] When a specific combination of source, analyzer, and detector becomes conventional in practice, a compound acronym may arise to designate it succinctly.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] One example is MALDI-TOF, which refers to a combination of a matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization source with a time-of-flight mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Other examples include inductively coupled plasma-mass spectrometry (ICP-MS), accelerator mass spectrometry, thermal ionization-mass spectrometry (TIMS) and spark source mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] Certain applications of mass spectrometry have developed monikers that although strictly speaking would seem to refer to a broad application, in practice have come instead to connote a specific or a limited number of instrument configurations.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p01] An example of this is isotope-ratio mass spectrometry, which refers in practice to the use of a limited number of sector based mass analyzers; this name is used to refer to both the application and the instrument used for the application.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] An important enhancement to the mass resolving and mass determining capabilities of mass spectrometry is using it in tandem with chromatographic and other separation techniques.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A common combination is gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC/MS or GC-MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In this technique, a gas chromatograph is used to separate different compounds.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This stream of separated compounds is fed online into the ion source, a metallic filament to which voltage is applied.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This filament emits electrons which ionize the compounds.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The ions can then further fragment, yielding predictable patterns.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Intact ions and fragments pass into the mass spectrometer's analyzer and are eventually detected.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] However, the high temperatures (300 °C) used in the GC-MS injection port (and oven) can result in thermal degradation of injected molecules, thus resulting in the measurement of degradation products instead of the actual molecule(s) of interest.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Similarly to gas chromatography MS (GC-MS), liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (LC/MS or LC-MS) separates compounds chromatographically before they are introduced to the ion source and mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] It differs from GC-MS in that the mobile phase is liquid, usually a mixture of water and organic solvents, instead of gas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Most commonly, an electrospray ionization source is used in LC-MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other popular and commercially available LC-MS ion sources are atmospheric pressure chemical ionization and atmospheric pressure photoionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] There are also some newly developed ionization techniques like laser spray.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Capillary electrophoresis–mass spectrometry (CE-MS) is a technique that combines the liquid separation process of capillary electrophoresis with mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] CE-MS is typically coupled to electrospray ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Ion mobility spectrometry-mass spectrometry (IMS/MS or IMMS) is a technique where ions are first separated by drift time through some neutral gas under an applied electrical potential gradient before being introduced into a mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Drift time is a measure of the collisional cross section relative to the charge of the ion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The duty cycle of IMS (the time over which the experiment takes place) is longer than most mass spectrometric techniques, such that the mass spectrometer can sample along the course of the IMS separation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This produces data about the IMS separation and the mass-to-charge ratio of the ions in a manner similar to LC-MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The duty cycle of IMS is short relative to liquid chromatography or gas chromatography separations and can thus be coupled to such techniques, producing triple modalities such as LC/IMS/MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry produces various types of data.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The most common data representation is the mass spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Certain types of mass spectrometry data are best represented as a mass chromatogram.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Types of chromatograms include selected ion monitoring (SIM), total ion current (TIC), and selected reaction monitoring, among many others.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other types of mass spectrometry data are well represented as a three-dimensional contour map.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In this form, the mass-to-charge, *m/z* is on the *x*-axis, intensity the *y*-axis, and an additional experimental parameter, such as time, is recorded on the *z*-axis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry data analysis is specific to the type of experiment producing the data.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] General subdivisions of data are fundamental to understanding any data.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Many mass spectrometers work in either *negative ion mode* or *positive ion mode*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] It is very important to know whether the observed ions are negatively or positively charged.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This is often important in determining the neutral mass but it also indicates something about the nature of the molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Different types of ion source result in different arrays of fragments produced from the original molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] An electron ionization source produces many fragments and mostly single-charged (1-) radicals (odd number of electrons), whereas an electrospray source usually produces non-radical quasimolecular ions that are frequently multiply charged.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Tandem mass spectrometry purposely produces fragment ions post-source and can drastically change the sort of data achieved by an experiment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Knowledge of the origin of a sample can provide insight into the component molecules of the sample and their fragmentations.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A sample from a synthesis/manufacturing process will probably contain impurities chemically related to the target component.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A crudely prepared biological sample will probably contain a certain amount of salt, which may form adducts with the analyte molecules in certain analyses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Results can also depend heavily on sample preparation and how it was run/introduced.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] An important example is the issue of which matrix is used for MALDI spotting, since much of the energetics of the desorption/ionization event is controlled by the matrix rather than the laser power.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Sometimes samples are spiked with sodium or another ion-carrying species to produce adducts rather than a protonated species.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry can measure molar mass, molecular structure, and sample purity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Each of these questions requires a different experimental procedure; therefore, adequate definition of the experimental goal is a prerequisite for collecting the proper data and successfully interpreting it.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Since the precise structure or peptide sequence of a molecule is deciphered through the set of fragment masses, the interpretation of mass spectra requires combined use of various techniques.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Usually the first strategy for identifying an unknown compound is to compare its experimental mass spectrum against a library of mass spectra.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] If no matches result from the search, then manual interpretation or software assisted interpretation of mass spectra must be performed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Computer simulation of ionization and fragmentation processes occurring in mass spectrometer is the primary tool for assigning structure or peptide sequence to a molecule.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] An *a priori* structural information is fragmented *in silico* and the resulting pattern is compared with observed spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Such simulation is often supported by a fragmentation library that contains published patterns of known decomposition reactions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Software taking advantage of this idea has been developed for both small molecules and proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Analysis of mass spectra can also be spectra with accurate mass.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A mass-to-charge ratio value (*m/z*) with only integer precision can represent an immense number of theoretically possible ion structures; however, more precise mass figures significantly reduce the number of candidate molecular formulas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A computer algorithm called formula generator calculates all molecular formulas that theoretically fit a given mass with specified tolerance.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry has both qualitative and quantitative uses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] These include identifying unknown compounds, determining the isotopic composition of elements in a molecule, and determining the structure of a compound by observing its fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Other uses include quantifying the amount of a compound in a sample or studying the fundamentals of gas phase ion chemistry (the chemistry of ions and neutrals in a vacuum).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] MS is now commonly used in analytical laboratories that study physical, chemical, or biological properties of a great variety of compounds.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Quantification can be relative (analyzed relative to a reference sample) or absolute (analyzed using a standard curve method).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A few of the disadvantages of the method is that it often fails to distinguish between optical and geometrical isomers and the positions of substituent in o-, m- and p- positions in an aromatic ring.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Also, its scope is limited in identifying hydrocarbons that produce similar fragmented ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry is also used to determine the isotopic composition of elements within a sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Differences in mass among isotopes of an element are very small, and the less abundant isotopes of an element are typically very rare, so a very sensitive instrument is required.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] For the measurement of light elements (e.g.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] H,C,N,O,S), isotope ratio mass spectrometers usually use a single magnet to bend a beam of ionized particles towards a series of Faraday cups which convert particle impacts to electric current.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A fast on-line analysis of deuterium content of water can be done using flowing afterglow mass spectrometry, FA-MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Probably the most sensitive and accurate mass spectrometer for this purpose is the accelerator mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This is because it provides ultimate sensitivity, capable of measuring individual atoms and measuring nuclides with a dynamic range of ~1015 relative to the major stable isotope.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Isotopic signatures can serve as markers of a variety of processes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Some isotope ratios are used to determine the age of materials for example as in carbon dating.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Labeling with stable isotopes is also used for protein quantification (see protein characterization below).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Membrane-introduction mass spectrometry combines the isotope ratio mass spectrometry with a reaction chamber/cell separated by a gas-permeable membrane.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This method allows the study of gases as they evolve in solution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This method has been extensively used for the study of the production of oxygen by Photosystem II.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Another technique with applications in trace gas analysis field is secondary electrospray ionization (SESI-MS), which is a variant of electrospray ionization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] SESI consist of an electrospray plume of pure acidified solvent that interacts with neutral vapors.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Vapor molecules get ionized at atmospheric pressure when charge is transferred from the ions formed in the electrospray to the molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] One advantage of this approach is that it is compatible with most ESI-MS systems.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A residual gas analyzer (RGA) is a small and usually rugged mass spectrometer, typically designed for process control and contamination monitoring in vacuum systems.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] When constructed as a quadrupole mass analyzer, there exist two implementations, utilizing either an open ion source (OIS) or a closed ion source (CIS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs may be found in high vacuum applications such as research chambers, surface science setups, accelerators, scanning microscopes, etc.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs are used in most cases to monitor the quality of the vacuum and easily detect minute traces of impurities in the low-pressure gas environment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] These impurities can be measured down to $10^{-14}$ Torr levels, possessing sub-ppm detectability in the absence of background interferences.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] RGAs would also be used as sensitive in-situ leak detectors commonly using helium, isopropyl alcohol or other tracer molecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] With vacuum systems pumped down to lower than $10^{-5}$ Torr—checking of the integrity of the vacuum seals and the quality of the vacuum—air leaks, virtual leaks and other contaminants at low levels may be detected before a process is initiated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] An atom probe is an instrument that combines time-of-flight mass spectrometry and field-evaporation microscopy to map the location of individual atoms.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Pharmacokinetics is often studied using mass spectrometry because of the complex nature of the matrix (often blood or urine) and the need for high sensitivity to observe low dose and long time point data.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The most common instrumentation used in this application is LC-MS with a triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Tandem mass spectrometry is usually employed for added specificity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Standard curves and internal standards are used for quantitation of usually a single pharmaceutical in the samples.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The samples represent different time points as a pharmaceutical is administered and then metabolized or cleared from the body.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Blank or t=0 samples taken before administration are important in determining background and ensuring data integrity with such complex sample matrices.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Much attention is paid to the linearity of the standard curve; however it is not uncommon to use curve fitting with more complex functions such as quadratics since the response of most mass spectrometers is less than linear across large concentration ranges.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] There is currently considerable interest in the use of very high sensitivity mass spectrometry for microdosing studies, which are seen as a promising alternative to animal experimentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Recent studies show that secondary electrospray ionization (SESI) is a powerful technique to monitor drug kinetics via breath analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Because breath is naturally produced, several datapoints can be readily collected.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This allows for the number of collected data-points to be greatly increased.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In animal studies, this approach SESI can reduce animal sacrifice.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In humans, SESI-MS non-invasive analysis of breath can help study the kinetics of drugs at a personalized level.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometry is an important method for the characterization and sequencing of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The two primary methods for ionization of whole proteins are electrospray ionization (ESI) and matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization (MALDI).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In keeping with the performance and mass range of available mass spectrometers, two approaches are used for characterizing proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In the first, intact proteins are ionized by either of the two techniques described above, and then introduced to a mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This approach is referred to as "top-down" strategy of protein analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The top-down approach however is largely limited to low-throughput single-protein studies.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In the second, proteins are enzymatically digested into smaller peptides using proteases such as trypsin or pepsin, either in solution or in gel after electrophoretic separation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The collection of peptide products are often separated by chromatography prior to introduction to the mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] When the characteristic pattern of peptides is used for the identification of the protein the method is called peptide mass fingerprinting (PMF), if the identification is performed using the sequence data determined in tandem MS analysis it is called de novo peptide sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] These procedures of protein analysis are also referred to as the "bottom-up" approach, and have also been used to analyse the distribution and position of post-translational modifications such as phosphorylation on proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A third approach is also beginning to be used, this intermediate "middle-down" approach involves analyzing proteolytic peptides that are larger than the typical tryptic peptide.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] As a standard method for analysis, mass spectrometers have reached other planets and moons.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Two were taken to Mars by the Viking program.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In early 2005 the Cassini–Huygens mission delivered a specialized GC-MS instrument aboard the Huygens probe through the atmosphere of Titan, the largest moon of the planet Saturn.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] This instrument analyzed atmospheric samples along its descent trajectory and was able to vaporize and analyze samples of Titan's frozen, hydrocarbon covered surface once the probe had landed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] These measurements compare the abundance of isotope(s) of each particle comparatively to earth's natural abundance.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Also on board the Cassini–Huygens spacecraft was an ion and neutral mass spectrometer which had been taking measurements of Titan's atmospheric composition as well as the composition of Enceladus' plumes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A Thermal and Evolved Gas Analyzer mass spectrometer was carried by the Mars Phoenix Lander launched in 2007.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometers are also widely used in space missions to measure the composition of plasmas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] For example, the Cassini spacecraft carried the Cassini Plasma Spectrometer (CAPS), which measured the mass of ions in Saturn's magnetosphere.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Mass spectrometers were used in hospitals for respiratory gas analysis beginning around 1975 through the end of the century.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Some are probably still in use but none are currently being manufactured.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Found mostly in the operating room, they were a part of a complex system, in which respired gas samples from patients undergoing anesthesia were drawn into the instrument through a valve mechanism designed to sequentially connect up to 32 rooms to the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] A computer directed all operations of the system.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The data collected from the mass spectrometer was delivered to the individual rooms for the anesthesiologist to use.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The uniqueness of this magnetic sector mass spectrometer may have been the fact that a plane of detectors, each purposely positioned to collect all of the ion species expected to be in the samples, allowed the instrument to simultaneously report all of the gases respired by the patient.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Although the mass range was limited to slightly over 120 u, fragmentation of some of the heavier molecules negated the need for a higher detection limit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The primary function of mass spectrometry is as a tool for chemical analyses based on detection and quantification of ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] However, mass spectrometry also shows promise for material synthesis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Ion soft landing is characterized by deposition of intact species on surfaces at low kinetic energies which precludes the fragmentation of the incident species.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] The soft landing technique was first reported in 1977 for the reaction of low energy sulfur containing ions on a lead surface.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] Most mass spectrometers measure the mass-to-charge ratio; the actual mass can be found only if the charge is known.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] For smaller molecules the charge can be determined from the spacing of isotope peaks, but for very large biomolecules and particles (in the megadalton range) resolution may not be adequate to separate isotope peaks, and thus the mass cannot be determined.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] In charge detection mass spectrometry (CDMS), the charge of an individual ion/particle is measured directly (alongside its mass-to-charge ratio) and therefore the true mass is known.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-spectrometry-p02] It is a single-particle technique, but to produce more precise and accurate results, the data from many individually-measured ions can be combined.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The **mass-to-charge ratio** (*m*/*Q*) is a physical quantity relating the *mass* (quantity of matter) and the *electric charge* of a given particle, expressed in units of kilograms per coulomb (kg/C).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] It is most widely used in the electrodynamics of charged particles, e.g. in electron optics and ion optics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] It appears in the scientific fields of electron microscopy, cathode ray tubes, accelerator physics, nuclear physics, Auger electron spectroscopy, cosmology and mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The importance of the mass-to-charge ratio, according to classical electrodynamics, is that two particles with the same mass-to-charge ratio move in the same path in a vacuum, when subjected to the same electric and magnetic fields.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Some disciplines use the **charge-to-mass** ratio (*Q*/*m*) instead, which is the multiplicative inverse of the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] where **F** is the force applied to the ion, *m* is the mass of the particle, **a** is the acceleration, *Q* is the electric charge, **E** is the electric field, and **v** × **B** is the cross product of the ion's velocity and the magnetic flux density.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Together with the particle's initial conditions, it completely determines the particle's motion in space and time in terms of *m*/*Q*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] When presenting data in a mass spectrum, it is common to use the dimensionless *m*/*z*, which denotes the dimensionless quantity formed by dividing the mass number of the ion by its charge number.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] This differential equation is the classic equation of motion of a charged particle in a vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Together with the particle's initial conditions, it determines the particle's motion in space and time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] It immediately reveals that two particles with the same *m*/*Q* ratio behave in the same way.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] This is why the mass-to-charge ratio is an important physical quantity in those scientific fields where charged particles interact with magnetic or electric fields.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] There are non-classical effects that derive from quantum mechanics, such as the Stern–Gerlach effect that can diverge the path of ions of identical *m*/*Q*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The IUPAC-recommended symbols for mass and charge are *m* and *Q*, respectively, however using a lowercase *q* for charge is also very common.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Charge is a scalar property, meaning that it can be either positive (+) or negative (−).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The Coulomb (C) is the SI unit of charge; however, other units can be used, such as expressing charge in terms of the elementary charge (*e*).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The SI unit of the physical quantity *m*/*Q* is kilogram per coulomb.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The units and notation above are used when dealing with the physics of mass spectrometry; however, the *m*/*z* notation is used for the independent variable in a mass spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] This notation eases data interpretation since it is numerically more related to the dalton.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] For example, if an ion carries one charge the *m*/*z* is numerically equivalent to the molecular or atomic mass of the ion in daltons (Da), where the numerical value of *m*/*Q* is abstruse.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The *m* refers to the molecular or atomic mass number (number of nucleons) and *z* to the charge number of the ion; however, the quantity of *m*/*z* is dimensionless by definition.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] An ion with a mass of 100 Da (daltons) (*m* = 100) carrying two charges (*z* = 2) will be observed at *m*/*z* 50.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] However, the empirical observation *m*/*z* 50 is one equation with two unknowns and could have arisen from other ions, such as an ion of mass 50 Da carrying one charge.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Thus, the *m*/*z* of an ion alone neither infers mass nor the number of charges.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Additional information, such as the mass spacing between mass isotopomers or the relationship between multiple charge states, is required to assign the charge state and infer the mass of the ion from the *m*/*z*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] This additional information is often but not always available.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Thus, the *m*/*z* is primarily used to report an empirical observation in mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] This observation may be used in conjunction with other lines of evidence to subsequently infer the physical attributes of the ion, such as mass and charge.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] On rare occasions, the thomson has been used as a unit of the x-axis of a mass spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] In the 19th century, the mass-to-charge ratios of some ions were measured by electrochemical methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The first attempt to measure the mass-to-charge ratio of cathode ray particles, assuming them to be ions, was made in 1884-1890 by German-born British physicist Arthur Schuster.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] He put an upper limit of 10^10 coul/kg, but even that resulted in much greater value than expected, so little credence was given to his calculations at the time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] In 1897, the mass-to-charge ratio of the electron was first measured by J.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] By doing this, he showed that the electron was in fact a particle with a mass and a charge, and that its mass-to-charge ratio was much smaller than that of the hydrogen ion H+.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] In 1898, Wilhelm Wien separated ions (canal rays) according to their mass-to-charge ratio with an ion optical device with superimposed electric and magnetic fields (Wien filter).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] In 1901 Walter Kaufman measured the increase of electromagnetic mass of fast electrons (Kaufmann–Bucherer–Neumann experiments), or relativistic mass increase in modern terms.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] In 1913, Thomson measured the mass-to-charge ratio of ions with an instrument he called a parabola spectrograph.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Today, an instrument that measures the mass-to-charge ratio of charged particles is called a mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The **charge-to-mass ratio** (*Q*/*m*) of an object is, as its name implies, the charge of an object divided by the mass of the same object.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] This quantity is generally useful only for objects that may be treated as particles.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] For extended objects, total charge, charge density, total mass, and mass density are often more useful.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] In some experiments, the charge-to-mass ratio is the only quantity that can be measured directly.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Often, the charge can be inferred from theoretical considerations, so the charge-to-mass ratio provides a way to calculate the mass of a particle.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Often, the charge-to-mass ratio can be determined by observing the deflection of a charged particle in an external magnetic field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The cyclotron equation, combined with other information such as the kinetic energy of the particle, will give the charge-to-mass ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] One application of this principle is the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The same principle can be used to extract information in experiments involving the cloud chamber.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The ratio of electrostatic to gravitational forces between two particles will be proportional to the product of their charge-to-mass ratios.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] It turns out that gravitational forces are negligible on the subatomic level, due to the extremely small masses of subatomic particles.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The electron charge-to-mass quotient, $-e/m_{e}$ , is a quantity that may be measured in experimental physics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] It bears significance because the electron mass *m*e is difficult to measure directly, and is instead derived from measurements of the elementary charge *e* and $e/m_{e}$ .
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] It also has historical significance; the *Q*/*m* ratio of the electron was successfully calculated by J.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Thomson in 1897—and more successfully by Dunnington, which involves the angular momentum and deflection due to a perpendicular magnetic field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Thomson's measurement convinced him that cathode rays were particles, which were later identified as electrons, and he is generally credited with their discovery.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] CODATA refers to this as the **electron charge-to-mass quotient**, but **ratio** is still commonly used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] There are two other common ways of measuring the charge-to-mass ratio of an electron, apart from Thomson and Dunnington's methods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Fine beam tube method: A heater heats a cathode, which emits electrons.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The electrons are accelerated through a known potential, so the velocity of the electrons is known.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The beam path can be seen when the electrons are accelerated through a helium (He) gas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] The collisions between the electrons and the helium gas produce a visible trail.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] A pair of Helmholtz coils produces a uniform and measurable magnetic field at right angles to the electron beam.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] This magnetic field deflects the electron beam in a circular path.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] By measuring the accelerating potential (volts), the current (amps) to the Helmholtz coils, and the radius of the electron beam, e/m can be calculated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] where **S** is the spin operator with eigenvalue *s* and **L** is the angular momentum operator with eigenvalue *l*.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/mass-to-charge-ratio] Measurements of the Zeeman effect commonly involve the use of a Fabry–Pérot interferometer, with light from a source (placed in a magnetic field) being passed between two mirrors of the interferometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] In mass spectrometry, the **quadrupole mass analyzer** (or **quadrupole mass filter**) is a type of mass analyzer originally conceived by Nobel laureate Wolfgang Paul and his student Helmut Steinwedel.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] As the name implies, it consists of four cylindrical rods, set parallel to each other.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] In a quadrupole mass spectrometer (QMS) the quadrupole is the *mass analyzer* – the component of the instrument responsible for selecting sample ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio (*m/z*).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Ions are separated in a quadrupole based on the stability of their trajectories in the oscillating electric fields that are applied to the rods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] The quadrupole consists of four parallel metal rods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Each opposing rod pair is connected together electrically, and a radio frequency (RF) voltage with a DC offset voltage is applied between one pair of rods and the other.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Ions travel down the quadrupole between the rods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Only ions of a certain mass-to-charge ratio will reach the detector for a given ratio of voltages: other ions have unstable trajectories and will collide with the rods.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] This permits selection of an ion with a particular *m/z* or allows the operator to scan for a range of *m/z*-values by continuously varying the applied voltage.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Mathematically this can be modeled with the help of the Mathieu differential equation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Ideally, the rods are hyperbolic, however cylindrical rods with a specific ratio of rod diameter-to-spacing provide an easier-to-manufacture adequate approximation to hyperbolas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Small variations in the ratio have large effects on resolution and peak shape.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Different manufacturers choose slightly different ratios to fine-tune operating characteristics in context of anticipated application requirements.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Since the 1980s, the MAT company and subsequently Finnigan Instrument Corporation used hyperbolic rods produced with a mechanical tolerance of 0.001 mm, whose exact production process was a well-kept secret within the company.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] A linear series of three quadrupoles is known as a triple quadrupole mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] The first (Q1) and third (Q3) quadrupoles act as mass filters, and the middle (q2) quadrupole is employed as a collision cell.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] This collision cell is an RF-only quadrupole (non-mass filtering) using Ar, He, or N2 gas (~10−3 Torr, ~30 eV) for collision induced dissociation of selected parent ion(s) from Q1.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Subsequent fragments are passed through to Q3 where they may be filtered or fully scanned.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] This process allows for the study of fragments that are useful in structural elucidation by tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] For example, the Q1 may be set to 'filter' for a drug ion of known mass, which is fragmented in q2.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] The third quadrupole (Q3) can then be set to scan the entire *m/z* range, giving information on the intensities of the fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Thus, the structure of the original ion can be deduced.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] The arrangement of three quadrupoles was first developed by Jim Morrison of La Trobe University in Australia for the purpose of studying the photodissociation of gas-phase ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] The first triple-quadrupole mass spectrometer was developed at Michigan State University by Christie Enke and graduate student Richard Yost in the late 1970s.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Quadrupoles can be used in hybrid mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] For example, a sector instrument can be combined with a collision quadrupole and quadrupole mass analyzer to form a hybrid instrument.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] A mass-selecting quadrupole and collision quadrupole with time-of-flight device as the second mass selection stage is a hybrid known as a quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometer (QTOF MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Quadrupole-quadrupole-time-of-flight (QqTOF) configurations are also possible and used especially the mass spectrometry of peptides and other large biological polymers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] A variant of the quadrupole mass analyzer called the monopole was invented by von Zahn which operates with two electrodes and generates one quarter of the quadrupole field.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] It has one circular electrode and one V-shaped electrode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] The performance is, however, lower than that of a quadrupole mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] An enhancement to the performance of the quadrupole mass analyzer has been demonstrated to occur when a magnetic field is applied to the instrument.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Manifold improvements in resolution and sensitivity have been reported for a magnetic field applied in various orientations to a QMS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] These mass spectrometers excel at applications where particular ions of interest are being studied because they can stay tuned on a single ion for extended periods of time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] One place where this is useful is in liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry or gas chromatography-mass spectrometry where they serve as exceptionally high specificity detectors.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] Quadrupole instruments are often reasonably priced and make good multi-purpose instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/quadrupole-mass-analyzer] A single quadrupole mass spectrometer with an electron impact ionizer is used as a standalone analyzer in residual gas analyzers, real-time gas analyzers, plasma diagnostics and SIMS surface analysis systems.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The molecules of a given sample are ionized and the first spectrometer (designated **MS1**) separates these ions by their mass-to-charge ratio (often given as **m/z** or m/Q).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Ions of a particular m/z-ratio coming from MS1 are selected and then made to split into smaller fragment ions, e.g. by collision-induced dissociation, ion-molecule reaction, or photodissociation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These fragments are then introduced into the second mass spectrometer (**MS2**), which in turn separates the fragments by their m/z-ratio and detects them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fragmentation step makes it possible to identify and separate ions that have very similar m/z-ratios in regular mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Typical tandem mass spectrometry instrumentation setups include triple quadrupole mass spectrometer (QqQ), multi-sector mass spectrometer, ion trap, quadrupole–time of flight (Q-TOF), Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR), and hybrid mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Triple quadrupole mass spectrometers use the first and third quadrupoles as mass filters.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When analytes pass the second quadrupole, the fragmentation proceeds through collision with gas.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Q-TOF mass spectrometers combine quadrupole and TOF instruments, which together enable fragmentation experiments that yield highly accurate mass quantitations for product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This is a method of mass spectrometry in which fragmented ion (*m*/*z*) ratios are determined through a time of flight measurement.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Hybrid mass spectrometers consist of more than two mass analyzers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Multiple stages of mass analysis separation can be accomplished with individual mass spectrometer elements separated in space or using a single mass spectrometer with the MS steps separated in time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For tandem mass spectrometry in space, the different elements are often noted in a shorthand, giving the type of mass selector used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In tandem mass spectrometry *in space*, the separation elements are physically separated and distinct, although there is a physical connection between the elements to maintain high vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These elements can be sectors, transmission quadrupole, or time-of-flight.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When using multiple quadrupoles, they can act as both mass analyzers and collision chambers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Common notation for mass analyzers is *Q* – quadrupole mass analyzer; *q* – radio frequency collision quadrupole; *TOF* – time-of-flight mass analyzer; *B* – magnetic sector, and *E* – electric sector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The notation can be combined to indicate various hybrid instrument, for example *QqQ'* – triple quadrupole mass spectrometer; *QTOF* – quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometer (also *QqTOF*); and *BEBE* – four-sector (reverse geometry) mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] By doing tandem mass spectrometry *in time*, the separation is accomplished with ions trapped in the same place, with multiple separation steps taking place over time.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A quadrupole ion trap or Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance instrument can be used for such an analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Trapping instruments can perform multiple steps of analysis, which is sometimes referred to as MS*n* (MS to the *n*).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Often the number of steps, *n*, is not indicated, but occasionally the value is specified; for example MS3 indicates three stages of separation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem in time MS instruments do not use the modes described next, but typically collect all of the information from a precursor ion scan and a parent ion scan of the entire spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Each instrumental configuration utilizes a unique mode of mass identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When tandem MS is performed with an in space design, the instrument must operate in one of a variety of modes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are a number of different tandem MS/MS experimental setups and each mode has its own applications and provides different information.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem MS in space uses the coupling of two instrument components which measure the same mass spectrum range but with a controlled fractionation between them in space, while tandem MS in time involves the use of an ion trap.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are four main scan experiments possible using MS/MS: precursor ion scan, product ion scan, neutral loss scan, and selected reaction monitoring.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For a precursor ion scan, the product ion is selected in the second mass analyzer, and the precursor masses are scanned in the first mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Note that precursor ion is synonymous with parent ion and product ion with daughter ion; however the use of these anthropomorphic terms is discouraged.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a product ion scan, a precursor ion is selected in the first stage, allowed to fragment and then all resultant masses are scanned in the second mass analyzer and detected in the detector that is positioned after the second mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This experiment is commonly performed to identify transitions used for quantification by tandem MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a neutral loss scan, the first mass analyzer scans all the masses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The second mass analyzer also scans, but at a set offset from the first mass analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This offset corresponds to a neutral loss that is commonly observed for the class of compounds.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In a constant-neutral-loss scan, all precursors that undergo the loss of a specified common neutral are monitored.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] To obtain this information, both mass analyzers are scanned simultaneously, but with a mass offset that correlates with the mass of the specified neutral.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Similar to the precursor-ion scan, this technique is also useful in the selective identification of closely related class of compounds in a mixture.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In selected reaction monitoring, both mass analyzers are set to a selected mass.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This mode is analogous to selected ion monitoring for MS experiments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A selective analysis mode, which can increase sensitivity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragmentation of gas-phase ions is essential to tandem mass spectrometry and occurs between different stages of mass analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] There are many methods used to fragment the ions and these can result in different types of fragmentation and thus different information about the structure and composition of the molecule.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Often, the ionization process is sufficiently violent to leave the resulting ions with sufficient internal energy to fragment within the mass spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] If the product ions persist in their non-equilibrium state for a moderate amount of time before auto-dissociation this process is called metastable fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Nozzle-skimmer fragmentation refers to the purposeful induction of in-source fragmentation by increasing the nozzle-skimmer potential on usually electrospray based instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Although in-source fragmentation allows for fragmentation analysis, it is not technically tandem mass spectrometry unless metastable ions are mass analyzed or selected before auto-dissociation and a second stage of analysis is performed on the resulting fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In-source fragmentation can be used in lieu of tandem mass spectrometry through the utilization of enhanced in-source fragmentation annotation (EISA) technology which generates fragmentation that directly matches tandem mass spectrometry data.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragments observed by EISA have higher signal intensity than traditional fragments which suffer losses in the collision cells of tandem mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] EISA enables fragmentation data acquisition on MS1 mass analyzers such as time-of-flight and single quadrupole instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In-source fragmentation is often used in addition to tandem mass spectrometry (with post-source fragmentation) to allow for two steps of fragmentation in a pseudo MS3-type of experiment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Post-source fragmentation is most often what is being used in a tandem mass spectrometry experiment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Energy can also be added to the ions, which are usually already vibrationally excited, through post-source collisions with neutral atoms or molecules, the absorption of radiation, or the transfer or capture of an electron by a multiply charged ion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Collision-induced dissociation (CID), also called collisionally activated dissociation (CAD), involves the collision of an ion with a neutral atom or molecule in the gas phase and subsequent dissociation of the ion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] where the ion AB+ collides with the neutral species M and subsequently breaks apart.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The details of this process are described by collision theory.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Due to different instrumental configuration, two main different types of CID are possible: *(i)* beam-type (in which precursor ions are fragmented on-the-flight) and *(ii)* ion trap-type (in which precursor ions are first trapped, and then fragmented).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A third and more recent type of CID fragmentation is higher-energy collisional dissociation (HCD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] HCD is a CID technique specific to orbitrap mass spectrometers in which fragmentation takes place external to the ion trap, it happens in the HCD cell (in some instruments named "ion routing multipole").
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] HCD is a trap-type fragmentation that has been shown to have beam-type characteristics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Freely available large scale high resolution tandem mass spectrometry databases exist (e.g.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] METLIN with 960,000 molecular standards each with experimental CID MS/MS data), and are typically used to facilitate small molecule identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The energy released when an electron is transferred to or captured by a multiply charged ion can induce fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] If an electron is added to a multiply charged positive ion, the Coulomb energy is liberated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Adding an electron through an ion-ion reaction is called electron-transfer dissociation (ETD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Similar to electron-capture dissociation, ETD induces fragmentation of cations (e.g. peptides or proteins) by transferring electrons to them.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Syka and Jarrod Marto at the University of Virginia.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] ETD cleaves randomly along the peptide backbone (c and z ions) while side chains and modifications such as phosphorylation are left intact.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The technique only works well for higher charge state ions (z>2), however relative to collision-induced dissociation (CID), ETD is advantageous for the fragmentation of longer peptides or even entire proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This makes the technique important for top-down proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Much like ECD, ETD is effective for peptides with modifications such as phosphorylation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Electron-transfer and higher-energy collision dissociation (EThcD) is a combination ETD and HCD where the peptide precursor is initially subjected to an ion/ion reaction with fluoranthene anions in a linear ion trap, which generates c- and z-ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In the second step HCD all-ion fragmentation is applied to all ETD derived ions to generate b- and y- ions prior to final analysis in the orbitrap analyzer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This method employs dual fragmentation to generate ion- and thus data-rich MS/MS spectra for peptide sequencing and PTM localization.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Following this transfer event, the electron-deficient anion undergoes internal rearrangement and fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] NETD is the ion/ion analogue of electron-detachment dissociation (EDD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] NETD is compatible with fragmenting peptide and proteins along the backbone at the Cα-C bond.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The resulting fragments are usually a•- and x-type product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Electron-detachment dissociation (EDD) is a method for fragmenting anionic species in mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It serves as a negative counter mode to electron capture dissociation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Negatively charged ions are activated by irradiation with electrons of moderate kinetic energy.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The result is ejection of electrons from the parent ionic molecule, which causes dissociation via recombination.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Reaction between positively charged peptides and cationic reagents, also known as charge transfer dissociation (CTD), has recently been demonstrated as an alternative high-energy fragmentation pathway for low-charge state (1+ or 2+) peptides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Initial reports are that CTD causes backbone Cα-C bond cleavage of peptides and provides a•- and x-type product ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] where $h\nu$ represents the photon absorbed by the ion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Ultraviolet lasers can be used, but can lead to excessive fragmentation of biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Infrared photons will heat the ions and cause dissociation if enough of them are absorbed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This process is called infrared multiphoton dissociation (IRMPD) and is often accomplished with a carbon dioxide laser and an ion trapping mass spectrometer such as a FTMS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Blackbody radiation can be used for photodissociation in a technique known as blackbody infrared radiative dissociation (BIRD).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In the BIRD method, the entire mass spectrometer vacuum chamber is heated to create infrared light.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] BIRD uses this radiation to excite increasingly more energetic vibrations of the ions, until a bond breaks, creating fragments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This is similar to infrared multiphoton dissociation which also uses infrared light, but from a different source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] BIRD is most often used with Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] With surface-induced dissociation (SID), the fragmentation is a result of the collision of an ion with a surface under high vacuum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Today, SID is used to fragment a wide range of ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Years ago, it was only common to use SID on lower mass, singly charged species because ionization methods and mass analyzer technologies weren't advanced enough to properly form, transmit, or characterize ions of high m/z.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Over time, self-assembled monolayer surfaces (SAMs) composed of CF3(CF2)10CH2CH2S on gold have been the most prominently used collision surfaces for SID in a tandem spectrometer.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] SAMs have acted as the most desirable collision targets due to their characteristically large effective masses for the collision of incoming ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Additionally, these surfaces are composed of rigid fluorocarbon chains, which don't significantly dampen the energy of the projectile ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fluorocarbon chains are also beneficial because of their ability to resist facile electron transfer from the metal surface to the incoming ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] SID's ability to produce subcomplexes that remain stable and provide valuable information on connectivity is unmatched by any other dissociation technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Since the complexes produced from SID are stable and retain distribution of charge on the fragment, this produces a unique, spectra which the complex centers around a narrower m/z distribution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The SID products and the energy at which they form are reflective of the strengths and topology of the complex.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The unique dissociation patterns help discover the Quaternary structure of the complex.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The symmetric charge distribution and dissociation dependence are unique to SID and make the spectra produced distinctive from any other dissociation technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The SID technique is also applicable to ion-mobility mass spectrometry (IM-MS).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Three different methods for this technique include analyzing the characterization of topology, intersubunit connectivity, and the degree of unfolding for protein structure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Analysis of protein structure unfolding is the most commonly used application of the SID technique.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For Ion-mobility mass spectrometry (IM-MS), SID is used for dissociation of the source activated precursors of three different types of protein complexes: C-reactive protein (CRP), transthyretin (TTR), and concanavalin A (Con A).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This method is used to observe the unfolding degree for each of these complexes.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For this observation, SID showed the precursor ions' structures that exist before the collision with the surface.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] IM-MS utilizes the SID as a direct measure of the conformation for each proteins' subunit.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fourier-transform ion cyclotron resonance are able to provide ultrahigh resolution and high mass accuracy to instruments that take mass measurements.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These features make FT-ICR mass spectrometers a useful tool for a wide variety of applications such as several dissociation experiments such as collision-induced dissociation (CID, electron transfer dissociation (ETD), and others.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] In addition, surface-induced dissociation has been implemented with this instrument for the study of fundamental peptide fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Specifically, SID has been applied to the study of energetics and the kinetics of gas-phase fragmentation within an ICR instrument.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This approach has been used to understand the gas-phase fragmentation of protonated peptides, odd-electron peptide ions, non-covalent ligand-peptide complexes, and ligated metal clusters.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Quantitative proteomics is used to determine the relative or absolute amount of proteins in a sample.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Several quantitative proteomics methods are based on tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] MS/MS has become a benchmark procedure for the structural elucidation of complex biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] One method commonly used for quantitative proteomics is isobaric tag labeling.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Isobaric tag labeling enables simultaneous identification and quantification of proteins from multiple samples in a single analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] To quantify proteins, peptides are labeled with chemical tags that have the same structure and nominal mass, but vary in the distribution of heavy isotopes in their structure.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These tags, commonly referred to as tandem mass tags, are designed so that the mass tag is cleaved at a specific linker region upon higher-energy collisional-induced dissociation (HCD) during tandem mass spectrometry yielding reporter ions of different masses.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Protein quantitation is accomplished by comparing the intensities of the reporter ions in the MS/MS spectra.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Two commercially available isobaric tags are iTRAQ and TMT reagents.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] An isobaric tag for relative and absolute quantitation (iTRAQ) is a reagent for tandem mass spectrometry that is used to determine the amount of proteins from different sources in a single experiment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It uses stable isotope labeled molecules that can form a covalent bond with the N-terminus and side chain amines of proteins.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The iTRAQ reagents are used to label peptides from different samples that are pooled and analyzed by liquid chromatography and tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The fragmentation of the attached tag generates a low molecular mass reporter ion that can be used to relatively quantify the peptides and the proteins from which they originated.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A tandem mass tag (TMT) is an isobaric mass tag chemical label used for protein quantification and identification.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The tags contain four regions: mass reporter, cleavable linker, mass normalization, and protein reactive group.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] TMT reagents can be used to simultaneously analyze 2 to 11 different peptide samples prepared from cells, tissues or biological fluids.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Recent developments allow up to 16 and even 18 samples (16plex or 18plex respectively) to be analyzed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The progress in data independent acquisition (DIA) enabled multiplexed quantitative proteomics with non-isobaric mass tags and a new method called plexDIA introduced in 2021.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] This new approach increases the number of data points by parallelizing both samples and peptides, thus achieving multiplicative gains.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It has the potential to continue scaling proteomic throughput with new mass tags and algorithms. plexDIA is applicable to both bulk and single-cell samples and is particularly powerful for single-cell proteomics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry can be used for protein sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] When intact proteins are introduced to a mass analyzer, this is called "top-down proteomics" and when proteins are digested into smaller peptides and subsequently introduced into the mass spectrometer, this is called "bottom-up proteomics".
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Shotgun proteomics is a variant of bottom up proteomics in which proteins in a mixture are digested prior to separation and tandem mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry can produce a peptide sequence tag that can be used to identify a peptide in a protein database.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A notation has been developed for indicating peptide fragments that arise from a tandem mass spectrum.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Peptide fragment ions are indicated by a, b, or c if the charge is retained on the N-terminus and by x, y or z if the charge is maintained on the C-terminus.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The subscript indicates the number of amino acid residues in the fragment.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Superscripts are sometimes used to indicate neutral losses in addition to the backbone fragmentation, * for loss of ammonia and ° for loss of water.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Although peptide backbone cleavage is the most useful for sequencing and peptide identification other fragment ions may be observed under high energy dissociation conditions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These include the side chain loss ions d, v, w and ammonium ions and additional sequence-specific fragment ions associated with particular amino acid residues.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Oligosaccharides may be sequenced using tandem mass spectrometry in a similar manner to peptide sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Fragmentation generally occurs on either side of the glycosidic bond (b, c, y and z ions) but also under more energetic conditions through the sugar ring structure in a cross-ring cleavage (x ions).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Again trailing subscripts are used to indicate position of the cleavage along the chain.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] For cross ring cleavage ions the nature of the cross ring cleavage is indicated by preceding superscripts.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry has been applied to DNA and RNA sequencing.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] A notation for gas-phase fragmentation of oligonucleotide ions has been proposed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Newborn screening is the process of testing newborn babies for treatable genetic, endocrinologic, metabolic and hematologic diseases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] The development of tandem mass spectrometry screening in the early 1990s led to a large expansion of potentially detectable congenital metabolic diseases that affect blood levels of organic acids.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] It has been shown that tandem mass spectrometry data is highly consistent across instrument and manufacturer platforms including quadrupole time-of-flight (QTOF) and Q Exactive instrumentation, especially at 20 eV.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry cannot be applied for single-cell analyses as it is insensitive to analyze such small amounts of a cell.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] These limitations are primarily due to a combination of inefficient ion production and ion losses within the instruments due to chemical noise sources of solvents.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] Tandem mass spectrometry will be a useful tool for protein characterization, nucleoprotein complexes, and other biological structures.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/tandem-mass-spectrometry] However, some challenges left such as analyzing the characterization of the proteome quantitatively and qualitatively.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] where *E*p is potential energy, *q* is the charge of the particle, and *U* is the electric potential difference (also known as voltage).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] When the charged particle is accelerated into *time-of-flight tube* (TOF tube or flight tube) by the voltage *U*, its potential energy is converted to kinetic energy.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The velocity of the charged particle after acceleration will not change since it moves in a field-free time-of-flight tube.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The velocity of the particle can be determined in a time-of-flight tube since the length of the path (*d*) of the flight of the ion is known and the time of the flight of the ion (*t*) can be measured using a transient digitizer or time to digital converter.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] These factors for the time of flight have been grouped purposely. ${\frac {d}{\sqrt {2U}}}$ contains constants that in principle do not change when a set of ions are analyzed in a single pulse of acceleration.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] where *k* is a proportionality constant representing factors related to the instrument settings and characteristics.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] (**9**) reveals more clearly that the time of flight of the ion varies with the square root of its mass-to-charge ratio (*m/q*).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Consider a real-world example of a MALDI time-of-flight mass spectrometer instrument which is used to produce a mass spectrum of the tryptic peptides of a protein.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Suppose the mass of one tryptic peptide is 1000 daltons (Da).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The kind of ionization of peptides produced by MALDI is typically +1 ions, so *q* = e in both cases.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Suppose the instrument is set to accelerate the ions in a *U* = 15,000 volts (15 kilovolt or 15 kV) potential.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] And suppose the length of the flight tube is 1.5 meters (typical).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Note that the mass had to be converted from daltons (Da) to kilograms (kg) to make it possible to evaluate the equation in the proper units.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] If there were a singly charged tryptic peptide ion with 4000 Da mass, and it is four times larger than the 1000 Da mass, it would take twice the time, or about 56 microseconds to traverse the flight tube, since time is proportional to the square root of the mass-to-charge ratio.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The ion equilibration in plasma plume produced during the desorption/ionization takes place approximately 100 ns or less, after that most of ions irrespectively of their mass start moving from the surface with some average velocity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Delayed extraction generally refers to the operation mode of vacuum ion sources when the onset of the electric field responsible for acceleration (extraction) of the ions into the flight tube is delayed by some short time (200–500 ns) with respect to the ionization (or desorption/ionization) event.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] This differs from a case of constant extraction field where the ions are accelerated instantaneously upon being formed.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Delayed extraction is used with MALDI or laser desorption/ionization (LDI) ion sources where the ions to be analyzed are produced in an expanding plume moving from the sample plate with a high speed (400–1000 m/s).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Since the thickness of the ion packets arriving at the detector is important to mass resolution, on first inspection it can appear counter-intuitive to allow the ion plume to further expand before extraction.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Delayed extraction is more of a compensation for the initial momentum of the ions: it provides the same arrival times at the detector for ions with the same mass-to-charge ratios but with different initial velocities.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] In delayed extraction of ions produced in vacuum, the ions that have lower momentum in the direction of extraction start to be accelerated at higher potential due to being further from the extraction plate when the extraction field is turned on.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Conversely, those ions with greater forward momentum start to be accelerated at lower potential since they are closer to the extraction plate.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] At the exit from the acceleration region, the slower ions at the back of the plume will be accelerated to greater velocity than the initially faster ions at the front of the plume.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] So after delayed extraction, a group of ions that leaves the ion source earlier has lower velocity in the direction of the acceleration compared to some other group of ions that leaves the ion source later but with greater velocity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] When ion source parameters are properly adjusted, the faster group of ions catches up to the slower one at some distance from the ion source, so the detector plate placed at this distance detects simultaneous arrival of these groups of ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] In its way, the delayed application of the acceleration field acts as a one-dimensional time-of-flight focusing element.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The kinetic energy distribution in the direction of ion flight can be corrected by using a reflectron.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The reflectron uses a constant electrostatic field to reflect the ion beam toward the detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The more energetic ions penetrate deeper into the reflectron, and take a slightly longer path to the detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Less energetic ions of the same mass-to-charge ratio penetrate a shorter distance into the reflectron and, correspondingly, take a shorter path to the detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The flat surface of the ion detector (typically a microchannel plate, MCP) is placed at the plane where ions of same m/z but with different energies arrive at the same time counted with respect to the onset of the extraction pulse in the ion source.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] A point of simultaneous arrival of ions of the same mass-to-charge ratio but with different energies is often referred as time-of-flight focus.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] An additional advantage to the re-TOF arrangement is that twice the flight path is achieved in a given length of the TOF instrument.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] A Bradbury–Nielsen shutter is a type of ion gate used in TOF mass spectrometers and in ion mobility spectrometers, as well as Hadamard transform TOF mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The Bradbury–Nielsen shutter is ideal for fast timed ion selector (TIS)—a device used for isolating ions over narrow mass range in tandem (TOF/TOF) MALDI mass spectrometers.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Continuous ion sources (most commonly electrospray ionization, ESI) are generally interfaced to the TOF mass analyzer by "orthogonal extraction" in which ions introduced into the TOF mass analyzer are accelerated along the axis perpendicular to their initial direction of motion.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Orthogonal acceleration combined with collisional ion cooling allows separating the ion production in the ion source and mass analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] In this technique, very high resolution can be achieved for ions produced in MALDI or ESI sources.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Before entering the orthogonal acceleration region or the pulser, the ions produced in continuous (ESI) or pulsed (MALDI) sources are focused (cooled) into a beam of 1–2 mm diameter by collisions with a residual gas in RF multipole guides.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] A system of electrostatic lenses mounted in high-vacuum region before the pulser makes the beam parallel to minimize its divergence in the direction of acceleration.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The combination of ion collisional cooling and orthogonal acceleration TOF has provided significant increase in resolution of modern TOF MS from few hundred to several tens of thousand without compromising the sensitivity.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Hadamard transform time-of flight mass spectrometry (HT-TOFMS) is a mode of mass analysis used to significantly increase the signal-to-noise ratio of a conventional TOFMS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Whereas traditional TOFMS analyzes one packet of ions at a time, waiting for the ions to reach the detector before introducing another ion packet, HT-TOFMS can simultaneously analyze several ion packets traveling in the flight tube.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The ions packets are encoded by rapidly modulating the transmission of the ion beam, so that lighter (and thus faster) ions from all initially released packets of mass from a beam get ahead of heavier (and thus slower) ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] This process creates an overlap of many time-of-flight distributions convoluted in form of signals.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The Hadamard transform algorithm is then used to carry out the deconvolution process which helps to produce a faster mass spectral storage rate than traditional TOFMS and other comparable mass separation instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometry (QToF-MS) has a similar configuration to a tandem mass spectrometer with a mass-resolving quadrupole and collision cell hexapole, but instead of a second mass-resolving quadrupole, a time-of-flight mass analyzer is used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Both quadrupoles can operate in RF mode only to allow all ions to pass through to the mass analyzer with minimal fragmentation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] To increase spectral detail, the system takes advantage of collision-induced dissociation.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Once the ions reach the flight tube, the ion pulser sends them upwards towards the reflectron and back down into the detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Since the ion pulser transfers the same kinetic energy to all molecules, the flight time is dictated by the mass of the analyte.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] QToF is capable of measuring mass to the 4th decimal place and is frequently used for pharmaceutical and toxicological analysis as a screening method for drug analogues.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Identification is done by collection of the mass spectrum and comparison to tandem mass spectrum libraries.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] A time-of-flight mass spectrometer (TOFMS) consists of a mass analyzer and a detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] An ion source (either pulsed or continuous) is used for lab-related TOF experiments, but not needed for TOF analyzers used in space, where the sun or planetary ionospheres provide the ions.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The TOF mass analyzer can be a linear flight tube or a reflectron.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The ion detector typically consists of microchannel plate detector or a fast secondary emission multiplier (SEM) where first converter plate (dynode) is flat.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The electrical signal from the detector is recorded by means of a time to digital converter (TDC) or a fast analog-to-digital converter (ADC).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] TDC is mostly used in combination with orthogonal-acceleration (oa)TOF instruments.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Time-to-digital converters register the arrival of a single ion at discrete time "bins"; a combination of threshold triggering and constant fraction discriminator (CFD) discriminates between electronic noise and ion arrival events.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] CFD converts nanosecond-long Gaussian-shaped electrical pulses of different amplitudes generated on the MCP's anode into common-shape pulses (e.g., pulses compatible with TTL/ESL logic circuitry) sent to TDC.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Using CFD provides a time point correspondent to a position of peak maximum independent of variation in the peak amplitude caused by variation of the MCP or SEM gain.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Double-hit resolution (dead time) of modern multi-hit TDC can be as low as 3-5 nanosecond.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The TDC is a counting detector – it can be extremely fast (down to a few picosecond resolution), but its dynamic range is limited due to its inability to properly count the events when more than one ion simultaneously (i.e., within the TDC dead time) hit the detector.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The outcome of limited dynamic range is that the number of ions (events) recorded in one mass spectrum is smaller compared to real number.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The problem of limited dynamic range can be alleviated using multichannel detector design: an array of mini-anodes attached to a common MCP stack and multiple CFD/TDC, where each CFD/TDC records signals from individual mini-anode.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] To obtain peaks with statistically acceptable intensities, ion counting is accompanied by summing of hundreds of individual mass spectra (so-called hystograming).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] To reach a very high counting rate (limited only by duration of individual TOF spectrum which can be as high as few milliseconds in multipath TOF setups), a very high repetition rate of ion extractions to the TOF tube is used.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Commercial orthogonal acceleration TOF mass analyzers typically operate at 5–20 kHz repetition rates.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] In combined mass spectra obtained by summing a large number of individual ion detection events, each peak is a histogram obtained by adding up counts in each individual bin.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Because the recording of the individual ion arrival with TDC yields only a single time point, the TDC eliminates the fraction of peak width determined by a limited response time of both the MCP detector and preamplifier.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] This propagates into better mass resolution.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Modern ultra-fast 10 GSample/sec analog-to-digital converters digitize the pulsed ion current from the MCP detector at discrete time intervals (100 picoseconds).
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Modern 8-bit or 10-bit 10 GHz ADC has much higher dynamic range than the TDC, which allows its usage in MALDI-TOF instruments with its high peak currents.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] To record fast analog signals from MCP detectors one is required to carefully match the impedance of the detector anode with the input circuitry of the ADC (preamplifier) to minimize the "ringing" effect.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Mass resolution in mass spectra recorded with ultra-fast ADC can be improved by using small-pore (2-5 micron) MCP detectors with shorter response times.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI) is a pulsed ionization technique that is readily compatible with TOF MS.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Atom probe tomography also takes advantage of TOF mass spectrometry.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Photoelectron photoion coincidence spectroscopy uses soft photoionization for ion internal energy selection and TOF mass spectrometry for mass analysis.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Secondary ion mass spectrometry commonly utilizes TOF mass spectrometers to allow parallel detection of different ions with a high mass resolving power.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Stefan Rutzinger proposed using TOF mass spectrometry with a cryogenic detector for the spectrometry of heavy biomolecules.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] An early time-of-flight mass spectrometer, named the Velocitron, was reported by A.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Eggers Jr, working at the Y-12 National Security Complex, in 1948.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] The idea had been proposed two years earlier, in 1946, by W.
[src:mass-spectrometry-chem/time-of-flight-mass-spectrometry] Stephens of the University of Pennsylvania in a Friday afternoon session of a meeting, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, of the American Physical Society.
